wp:comment.wp:comment_content:
Hi Joe,

You don't really need to store anywhere the numbers you have already found as double squares ( the $squares array).
It is easy to proove, that one of the additives should alwasy be &lt;= sqrt(number/2)
That is because if
number == i*i + i*i, then
number == 2*i*i 
i = sqrt(number/2)
So you just need a counter to count from 0 to sqrt(number/2) and another from sqrt(number/2) up to sqrt(number).


My solution is something like this (pseudo):
sq := sqrt(number);
halfSq := sqrt(number/2);
for( 0 &lt;= i &lt;= halfSq)
  for(halfSq &lt;= j &lt;= sq)
     if(i*i + j*j == number)
        doubleSq++;

Hi,

I also wrote a function which halfes the squares in a similar way to Joe's solution but used two counters:

[php]
function count_squares($n) {
    $x = (int)sqrt($n);
    $y = 0;
    $r = 0;

    while ($y &lt;= $x) {

        $sum = $x * $x + $y * $y;

        if ($sum &lt; $n) {
            ++$y; continue;
        }

        if ($sum &gt; $n) {
            --$x; continue;
        }
        ++$r; ––$x; ++$y;
    }
    return $r;
}
[/php]
I think the best solution has also a complexity of O(sqrt(n)).

as there are less integers between sqrt(number/2) and sqrt(number) than between 0 and sqrt(number/2), my solution is something like this (pseudo) i just check if the value (number-i*i) is a perfect square itself:

[code]
sq := sqrt(number);
halfSq := sqrt(number/2);
for( halfSq &lt;= i &lt;= sq)
if(sqrt(number-i*i) MOD 1 == 0) 
   doubleSq++;
[/code]

